      "content": "The perception that originalism is a \"conservative tool\" stems from the fact that the Supreme Court has historically been a conservative institution, and conservative judges have been the ones to champion this methodology. While liberals can certainly use originalism to defend their own positions, the theory's rigid adherence to the text often forces outcomes that liberals find inconvenient, such as striking down modern civil rights protections or limiting executive power. This isn't a flaw in the theory itself, but rather a reflection of how the current political landscape and the composition of the Court have skewed its application. A truly neutral theory would indeed appear evenly across the spectrum, but the reality is that the Court has long been a conservative court, and originalism is simply the lens through which they view the Constitution.",
